<h4>Rate of Change of Linear Functions.</h4>
<p>¬†The graph of a linear function is identical to the graph of the linear equation that describes it. The rate of change of a linear equation is constant. The rate of change is the slope, \(m=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}\)</p>
<ol class="os-raise-noindent">
<li>Find the rate of change of a linear function from a graph.</li>
</ol>
<p><img alt="Graph of a line passing through the points (16, 1) and (24, 1.5)." src="https://k12.openstax.org/contents/raise/resources/4498b4f9f306c3d58091822d5829c8d2075c8592" width="300"/></p>
<p>The rate of change of a linear function is constant, so you can choose any 2 points to find the slope.</p>
<p>Use \((16, 1)\) and \((24, 1.5)\).¬†</p>
<p>\(m=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}=\frac{1.5-1}{24-16}=\frac{0.5}{8}=\frac{1}{16}\)</p>
<p>The rate of change is \(\frac{1}{16}\)</p>
